  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international guidelines introduced\n- Limited scope of financial regulations\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Expanded international cooperation\n- Development of global anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Stricter customer identification protocols\n- Increased financial institution accountability\n\n4. Modern Approaches\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Risk-based compliance frameworks\n- Advanced technological detection mechanisms\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Integration of artificial intelligence in detection\n- Expanded definitions of financial crimes\n\n6. Current Focus Areas\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Sophisticated transaction tracking\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislative landscape continues to adapt, emphasizing comprehensive, technology-driven approaches to preventing financial crimes.",
